"about 1185":"circa 1185","1280":"1280","Italy":"Italië"},"en":{"about 1185–":"about 1185–Deceased","1185–Female":"1185–Deceased","1182–1252":"1182–1252","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1182–1196":"1182–1196","1215":"1215","1252":"1252","ABT 1215":"about 1215","1196":"1196","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","about 1185":"about 1185","1280":"1280","Italy":"Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"di","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 狄, a term referring to the tribes in ancient northern China: (i) from Di (狄), the name of an ancient state (thought to have been located in Hebei or Shandong province), which was granted to Xiao Bo or Kao Bo by King Cheng of Zhou (reigned 1042–1021  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Ku Di (庫狄) family during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) traced back to other minority ethnic groups in ancient northwestern China.","Mandarin form of the Chinese surname 邸, meaning ‘official residence’ in Chinese: (i) from placename Di (邸), the name of a county (unidentified location). (ii) said to be borne by some descendants of Kujula Kadphises (called 丘就郤 or 邸就郤 in Chinese, 30–<i>c.</i> 80  AD ), founder of the Kushan Empire (one branch of the Yuezhi people originating from western China) located in Central Asia during the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Chi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Dong, Yun, Cheng, Jae, Yong, Cheng Chung, Chi, Chun, Duk, Fang, Feng.  Korean Chung, Chong, Jae Hong, Moon, Myong, Pong, Shen, Yoo, Byung, Chang, Chol, Chong Hun.  Southeast Asian Phi, Hung, Ly, Tu, Denh, Do Van, Duong, Hao, Kieu, Mui, Nga, Phat.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 池, meaning ‘moat’ in ancient Chinese: (i) acquired as a surname by people who lived beside a moat. (ii) from Chi (池), said to be the name of an ancient state (of unknown location and period). (iii) from the personal name Chi (池), personal name of a son of an official in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 遲, meaning ‘late’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of Chi Ren (遲任), a person who lived during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the Chinese compound surname Yu-Chi (尉遲), originally the name of a tribe from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iii) from the second element of the personal name Zi Chi (子遲), style name of Fan Xu, a student of Confucius (551–479  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Molise","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Swedish   Molin  .","Catalan (<b>Moliné</b>): occupational name for a miller, from <i>moliner</i> miller. This surname is also found in southern France.","French and Jewish (from France): altered form of   Molina  , a surname of Spanish and Catalan origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Molina","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Manuel, Jesus, Francisco, Jorge, Mario, Miguel, Ana, Roberto.  Portuguese Joao, Margarida.","Spanish, Catalan, and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from any of numerous places called Molina, in particular the one in Guadalajara province. This surname is also found in France (compare   Moline  ). For certain Jewish families, this is an adoption of the Iberian surname at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."]},{"name":"Molin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Lars, Gunard, Jarl, Nils.  French Moliere, Pascale, Victoire.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name from <i>mo</i> ‘sandy heath’ + the suffix <i>-lin</i>, derived from Latin <i>-(l)inius</i> ‘relating to’, or from the root of Latin <i>molinarius</i> ‘miller’ or <i>mola</i> ‘mill’ + the suffix <i>-in</i>, derived from Latin <i>-inius</i> ‘relating to’.","Italian (Veneto): variant of   Molino  ."]}]},{"name":"Iodetta","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An Old English form of the name Violet."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Contessa Iodetta di Molise was born about 1185, her father, Comte Tomaso Di Celano, was 5 and her mother, Contessa Iodetta Di Molise, was 1. She had at least 1 son with Comte Tomaso di Celano."},"et":{"about 1185–":"umbes 1185–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1182–1252":"1182–1252","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1182–1196":"1182–1196","1215":"1215","1252":"1252","ABT 1215":"umbes 1215","1196":"1196","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","about 1185":"umbes 1185","1280":"1280","Italy":"Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1185–":"noin 1185–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1182–1252":"1182–1252","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1182–1196":"1182–1196","1215":"1215","1252":"1252","ABT 1215":"noin 1215","1196":"1196","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","about 1185":"noin 1185","1280":"1280","Italy":"Italia"},"fr":{"about 1185–":"environ 1185–Décédée","1185–Female":"1185–Décédée","1182–1252":"1182–1252","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1182–1196":"1182–1196","1215":"1215","1252":"1252","ABT 1215":"environ 1215","1196":"1196","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","about 1185":"environ 1185","1280":"1280","Italy":"Italie","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Contessa Iodetta di Molise est née environ 1185, son père, Comte Tomaso Di Celano, avait 5 ans et sa mère, Contessa Iodetta Di Molise, avait 1 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Comte Tomaso di Celano."},"de":{"about 1185–":"um 1185–Verstorben","1185–Female":"1185–Verstorben","1182–1252":"1182–1252","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1182–1196":"1182–1196","1215":"1215","1252":"1252","ABT 1215":"um 1215","1196":"1196","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","about 1185":"um 1185","1280":"1280","Italy":"Italien","lifeSummary":"Als Contessa Iodetta di Molise um 1185 geboren wurde, war ihr Vater Comte Tomaso Di Celano 5 und ihre Mutter Contessa Iodetta Di Molise